    "rationale": "This example demonstrates the oxidation of a secondary alcohol (4-tert-butylcyclohexanol) to the corresponding ketone (4-tert-butylcyclohexanone) using the Pfitzner-Moffatt protocol. The substrate is a simple, non-trivial cyclic alcohol, making it a clear and representative example of this transformation. The bulky tert-butyl group locks the conformation, but the reaction proceeds effectively. This avoids overly simple substrates like propan-2-ol or complex natural products.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is 4-tert-butylcyclohexanol, a common but specific starting material that is unlikely to be a generic seed for all alcohol oxidations. The product is the corresponding ketone. This specific substrate/product pair is distinct from simple linear alcohols or other common cyclic systems like adamantanol, reducing the risk of being flagged as a generic template.",
